Trump=E2=80=99s Senate Thune-Up
-------------------------

The House speaker=E2=80=99s race made blindingly obvious just how
much Mike Johnson=E2=80=99s political life depends on Donald Trump, but the=
 incoming president may be facing a less-obedient legislative leader across=
 the Rotunda in the form of Senate Majority Leader John Thune. Johnson, hav=
ing retained his gavel only by dint of Trump=E2=80=99s last-minute arm-twis=
ting, can be expected to try to keep his House members in line behind the p=
resident-elect=E2=80=99s agenda. But Thune, who won his leadership post wit=
hout Trump=E2=80=99s
endorsement, is sending signals that the Senate won=E2=80=99t be as complia=
nt.=C2=A0=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Two days after Trump intervened to flip Ralph Norman and Keith Self to John=
son=E2=80=99s side, Thune appeared on Face the Nation and told Margaret Bre=
nnan that, while he and the president-elect shared a =E2=80=9Cset of object=
ives=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cwant to get to the same destination,=E2=80=9D he
expected =E2=80=9Cthere will be differences in how we get there.=E2=80=9D H=
e also engaged in some expectations management, saying he was going to =E2=
=80=9Chave to be able to share and convey to the president and help him und=
erstand =E2=80=A6 what the contours are, what we can accomplish here in the=
 Senate, and what=E2=80=99s realistic.=E2=80=9D

=C2=A0

Trump, despite being the dominant figure in the G.O.P., is not the primary =
constituency for either
Johnson or Thune=E2=80=94both answer to their rank-and-file members. But as=
 any self-respecting Senate snob will tell you, the two chambers are entire=
ly different beasts, even when they=E2=80=99re controlled by the same party=
=2E The House may be fractious, but Rep=
ublicans proved docile to Trump on Fri=
day. The Senate, on the other hand, still includes a half-dozen moderate Re=
publicans whose reputations require that they occasionally buck the party l=
eader.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Yes, Johnson must manage a miserable margin. But as we saw on Friday, the T=
rump come-to-Jesus phone call can be effective on a lonely House dissenter =
or two. Senate egos require much more massaging. Lisa Murkowski and Susan C=
ollins have withstood Trumpian pressure before, and more broadly, six-year =
Senate terms insulate members from the immediate wrath of Trump voters.=C2=
=A0

=C2=A0

Anyway, Thune may be all-in on Trump=E2=80=99s policy wishlist=E2=80=94defe=
nse, the border, tax cuts, etcetera=E2=80=94but his comments make plain tha=
t the Senate G.O.P. is still less likely to be a knee-jerk, rubber-stamp bo=
dy, at least in the short term. The party preserved the filibuster on polic=
y votes, keeping in place an arcane Senate tradition in lieu of removing a =
potentially large obstacle to passing major Trump priorities through the ch=
amber. And Thune hasn=E2=80=99t expressed
much eagerness to use recess appointments for Trump=E2=80=99s nominees=E2=
=80=94a tactic that would handicap the Senate=E2=80=99s powers.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

On Sunday, Thune didn=E2=80=99t offer assurances that all of Trump=E2=80=99=
s nominees will be confirmed, but instead promised =E2=80=9Ca fair process=
=E2=80=9D that will involve input from committees and their territorial cha=
irs. =E2=80=9CWhen it comes to his picks=E2=80=94and I would say this of an=
y president=E2=80=94they deserve a lot of latitude. His picks are
going to come through a process where, if they get reported out of the comm=
ittee, come across the floor of the Senate, we=E2=80=99ll make sure that th=
ey get the vote,=E2=80=9D Thune said. =E2=80=9CI suspect a lot of them will=
 get through. All of them remains to be seen. But I think that=E2=80=99s wh=
y we have the process, adhere to that process, and give all of these nomine=
es an opportunity to make their case.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

Trump=E2=80=99s Need for Speed

***************************************************************************=
