***************************************************************************=
************************************************************************
Trump=E2=80=99s Need for Speed ( https://puck.news/trumps-second-term-need-=
for-speed/?utm_campaign=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F6=
%2F25%29&utm_content=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F6%2F=
25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c6061=
7da42abd12a )
***************************************************************************=
***************************************************************************=
***************************************************************************=
************************************************************************

Republicans are racing against an 18-month deadline to jam through
their agenda before a likely midterm shakeup, and Trump=E2=80=99s inevitabl=
e lame-duck status, make legislation impossible. Meanwhile, Democrats Adam =
Schiff and Ritchie Torres are preparing a playbook to capitalize on G.O.P. =
overreach.

Peter Hamby ( https://puck.news/author/peter-hamby/?utm_campaign=3DThe+Best=
+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F6%2F25%29&utm_content=3DThe+Best+%2=
6+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F6%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&ut=
m_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )
Peter Hamby ( https://puck.news/author/peter-hamby/?utm_campaign=3DThe+Best=
+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F6%2F25%29&utm_content=3DThe+Best+%2=
6+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%281%2F6%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&ut=
m_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

Republicans have been talking a lot lately about speed.
On Monday, Republican Congressman Mike Lawler told CNN=E2=80=99s Jake Tappe=
r that he and other G.O.P. members will be flying down to Mar-a-Lago this w=
eekend=E2=80=94even before Donald Trump is sworn in=E2=80=94to strategize o=
n a new tax bill. Incoming White House chief of staff Susie Wiles told Axio=
s that her plan for Trump 2.0 includes =E2=80=9Cgetting off to a quick star=
t and staying on that pace.=E2=80=9D And there was Trump, himself, calling =
into the Hugh
Hewitt show this morning to discuss whether Republicans should pursue a sin=
gle massive budget reconciliation bill with all the G.O.P. menu items bundl=
ed together=E2=80=94=E2=80=9Cone big, beautiful bill=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94or de=
al with the border and taxes in separate bills. Trump said he=E2=80=99d be =
open to either, =E2=80=9Cas long as we get something passed as quickly as p=
ossible.=E2=80=9D

=C2=A0

Trump and his deputies are communicating something critical in
the days before his second term begins. Even as he returns to office with f=
ull Republican control of government, unrivaled attentional powers, and Ova=
l Office experience under his belt, Trump simply doesn=E2=80=99t have the t=
ime to push all his campaign promises through Congress before his presidenc=
y starts to give off the stench of lame duck. Sure, he made history in Nove=
mber by winning the presidency again after four years in exile. But he also=
 made history in a way that doesn=E2=80=99t exactly work
in his favor: Trump is now the first president in the post-F.D.R. era to be=
 limited by law to just a single term.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Unlike in 2017, when a shell-shocked Washington establishment was contempla=
ting the horror of an eight-year Trump run, D.C. pros this time around are =
mostly just eyeing the next two years. Trump is a known commodity. The midt=
erm season arrives in 18 months or so, and
Democrats could easily flip the House. After that, media attention inevitab=
ly drifts to the next presidential election and the long primary process. S=
ure, by that time, the 81-year-old Trump will still have the nuclear codes =
and the power of the executive order. But as George W. Bush, Barack Obama, =
Trump 1.0, and Joe Biden learned, presidents usually just walk through mud =
in their final two years before leaving office.

=C2=A0

This is why Republicans are so determined to jam their agenda through using=
 the budget reconciliation process, which requires only a simple majority v=
ote for passage. But right now, Republicans are working with just a one-vot=
e margin in the House, meaning they need absolute party unity to pass a bor=
der bill or a tax bill or one big, beautiful bill. And Trump will never hav=
e more political capital than he does on January 19.
=E2=80=9CTime is not on their side,=E2=80=9D said Ron Bonjean, a longtime R=
epublican strategist and veteran of many Capitol Hill battles. =E2=80=9CThe=
 first two years are going to matter greatly, here. People talk about the f=
irst 100 days, but it=E2=80=99s probably going to take six to seven months =
to get their significant legislation through, whatever it looks like. And t=
hat is paramount, because then the House campaign cycle starts to kick in, =
with primaries and all the positioning that comes with it.=E2=80=9D

=C2=A0

Another plugged-in Republican veteran of Capitol Hill I spoke with Monday w=
as not as charitable when I asked if Trump will be able to muscle through w=
hatever he wants. The tax bill will have to get done somehow, this person t=
old me, simply because the 2017 law is expiring this year. As for everythin=
g else? =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t think that they are going to get a lot don=
e,=E2=80=9D this person said. =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t know Susie Wiles tha=
t
well. She seems to have a good rep. But with the combination of Trump=E2=80=
=99s lack of discipline, and the House being a complete shitshow, they=E2=
=80=99ll be lucky to get anything big done. The Senate, I think, will be an=
 oasis of normalcy.=E2=80=9D

=C2=A0

California Senator Adam Schiff=E2=80=94one of Trump=E2=80=99s most vocal De=
mocratic critics, newly promoted from the House=E2=80=94told me Monday that=
 Republicans are setting up an aggressive voting
schedule for the new Congress, suggesting they can=E2=80=99t risk losing th=
e early momentum. =E2=80=9CThey seem to see a very narrow window in which t=
o act on a partisan level, with a very narrow majority,=E2=80=9D Schiff sai=
d. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s clear they want to jam things through on a partisa=
n basis. So it=E2=80=99s one big reconciliation bill, or two, so they can c=
ram in as much as they can. But in the House, it will be tough for them to =
get their own people on board.=E2=80=9D

The Mega-Bill Black Hole
------------------------

While chatting with Bonjean, I was reminded of the long slog of the
Inflation Reduction Act, originally the Build Back Better Plan=E2=80=94Bide=
n=E2=80=99s landmark domestic spending legislation introduced back in Augus=
t of 2021. It=E2=80=99s easy to forget today, given Biden=E2=80=99s dismal =
public standing, but at the time, he had an approval rating over 50 percent=
 and was still basking in the honeymoon glow of his new presidency and the =
end of the pandemic. But by the time the I.R.A. was finally passed, a year =
later, Biden=E2=80=99s approval ratings were in the toilet, and the legisla=
tion had been
stripped down and revised after repeated drubbings from Joe Manchin and Kyr=
sten Sinema. It was still a victory, but it was really all Biden could extr=
act from Congress, and it took an entire year. Trump and his crew are hopin=
g to do something similar on an even shorter time horizon.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Bonjean said he=E2=80=99s confident that Trump=E2=80=94and Republican membe=
rs of Congress=E2=80=94have
learned enough about each other over the years to work together, =E2=80=9Cp=
lay the inside game,=E2=80=9D and pass something big. The Trump transition,=
 too, seems to be humming under the disciplined management of Wiles=E2=80=
=94although I would point out that the veteran Florida campaign operative i=
s just that: a campaign operative with relatively little experience calling=
 shots in Washington.

=C2=A0

Still, even with majority control in Congress, Bonjean
said, getting a major bill passed before the end of the year will make for =
a wild ride. =E2=80=9CThe challenge for one of these large, comprehensive m=
ega-bills is that, over time, they collapse under their own weight. Eventua=
lly, it becomes necessary to get it done under pressure, because everyone=
=E2=80=99s political livelihood depends on it. Again, it means time is not =
on their side. The funny thing about a unified Congress is that everyone=E2=
=80=99s priority becomes a top priority. Every committee chairman
has a priority that they think is the most important. House and Senate lead=
ership have theirs. It will take time to figure out.=E2=80=9D

Overreach & Inevitability
-------------------------

What do Democrats think of Trump=E2=80=99s prospects the second time
around? There are, of course, permanent anxieties on the left about Trump s=
ubverting the Constitution to stay in office for a third term come 2028. Bu=
t I actually haven=E2=80=99t heard that sentiment very much from Democrats =
since the election. I=E2=80=99ve heard sadness and confusion about their lo=
sses in November, sure. But I haven=E2=80=99t detected the existential Trum=
p dread that dominated Democratic politics in 2017 and 2018, when the #Resi=
stance was everything and Democracy Was Dying in Darkness. Instead, I=E2=80=
=99ve
been picking up an odd sort of calm determination about holding on through =
a second Trump term, and some cold comfort in the fact that they can see ar=
ound the corner to the end of his time in office.

=C2=A0

When I talked to Schiff today=E2=80=94on January 6, of all days=E2=80=94he =
told me he was confident that Trump will screw up, stir up public oppositio=
n with this issue or that, and generally do the work of making himself
unpopular. =E2=80=9CWe obviously can=E2=80=99t wait for years to solve the =
problems we have, and we should work with Republicans where we can, and sta=
nd up to him where we can, especially when he wants to give big tax cuts to=
 cronies,=E2=80=9D Schiff told me. =E2=80=9CBut look, it will be no time at=
 all before the Republicans are at each other=E2=80=99s throats, before peo=
ple in the White House are at each other=E2=80=99s throats. The last four y=
ears? That was them throwing each other under the bus all the time. The que=
stion is, who gets
thrown under the bus this time? And when they try to pick fights, they will=
 overreach on certain issues. That will inevitably come.=E2=80=9D

I asked another outspoken Democrat, New York=E2=80=99s Ritchie Torres, a si=
milar question: How should Democrats approach a president with a four-year =
shelf life and an unruly Republican House known mostly for dysfunction? Tor=
res=E2=80=99 response was, essentially, Let them burn. =E2=80=9CNot only is=
 Trump ill-fated to be a one-term
president for four years, he has a Republican Congress with only the illusi=
on of control,=E2=80=9D Torres told me. =E2=80=9CThe Republican majority in=
 the House of Representatives is so vanishingly small that nothing of conse=
quence can happen without the buy-in of House Democrats. Trump might feel m=
ore emboldened than ever before, but he will find himself more constrained =
in his second presidency than he was in his first. The realities of divided=
 government will trump any delusions of grandeur on Trump=E2=80=99s
part.=E2=80=9D

