line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">The House speaker=E2=80=99s race made <em>blind=
ingly</em> obvious just how
much <strong>Mike Johnson</strong>=E2=80=99s political life depends on <str=
ong>Donald Trump</strong>, but the incoming president may be facing a less-=
obedient legislative leader across the Rotunda in the form of Senate Majori=
ty Leader <strong>John Thune</strong>. Johnson, having retained his gavel o=
nly by dint of Trump=E2=80=99s last-minute arm-twisting, can be expected to=
 try to keep his House members in line behind the president-elect=E2=80=99s=
 agenda. But Thune, who won his leadership post without Trump=E2=80=99s
endorsement, is sending signals that the Senate won=E2=80=99t be as complia=
nt.=C2=A0=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Two days after Trump intervened to flip=
 <strong>Ralph Norman </strong>and<strong> Keith Self </strong>to Johnson=
=E2=80=99s side, Thune appeared on <em>Face the Nation</em> and told <stron=
g>Margaret Brennan</strong> that, while he and the president-elect shared a=
 =E2=80=9Cset of objectives=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cwant to get to the same d=
estination,=E2=80=9D he
expected =E2=80=9Cthere will be differences in how we get there.=E2=80=9D H=
e also engaged in some expectations management, saying he was going to =E2=
=80=9Chave to be able to share and convey to the president and help him und=
erstand =E2=80=A6 what the contours are, what we can accomplish here in the=
 Senate, and what=E2=80=99s realistic.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin:0;mar=
gin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Trump, =
despite being <em>the</em> dominant figure in the G.O.P., is not the primar=
y constituency for either
Johnson or Thune=E2=80=94both answer to their rank-and-file members. But as=
 any self-respecting Senate snob will tell you, the two chambers are entire=
ly different beasts, even when they=E2=80=99re controlled by the same party=
=2E The House may be fractious, but Rep=
ublicans proved docile to Trump on Fri=
day. The Senate, on the other hand, still includes a half-dozen moderate Re=
publicans whose reputations require that they occasionally buck the party l=
eader.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Yes, Johnson must manage a miserab=
le margin. But as we saw on Friday, the Trump come-to-Jesus phone call can =
be effective on a lonely House dissenter or two. Senate egos require much m=
ore massaging. <strong>Lisa Murkowski </strong>and<strong> Susan Collins</s=
trong> have withstood Trumpian pressure before, and more broadly, six-year =
Senate terms insulate members from the immediate wrath of Trump voters.=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Anyway, Thune may be all-in on Tru=
mp=E2=80=99s policy wishlist=E2=80=94defense, the border, tax cuts, etceter=
a=E2=80=94but his comments make plain that the Senate G.O.P. is still less =
likely to be a knee-jerk, rubber-stamp body, at least in the short term. Th=
e party preserved the filibuster on policy votes, keeping in place an arcan=
e Senate tradition in lieu of removing a potentially large obstacle to pass=
ing major Trump priorities through the chamber. And Thune hasn=E2=80=99t ex=
pressed
