ng-bottom:32px;"><div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39=
;Inter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0=
px;line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Republicans have been talking <em>a lot</e=
m> lately about speed.
On Monday, Republican Congressman <strong>Mike Lawler</strong> told CNN=E2=
=80=99s <strong>Jake Tapper</strong> that he and other G.O.P. members will =
be flying down to Mar-a-Lago this weekend=E2=80=94even before <strong>Donal=
d Trump</strong> is sworn in=E2=80=94to strategize on a new tax bill. Incom=
ing White House chief of staff <strong>Susie Wiles</strong> told Axios that=
 her plan for Trump 2.0 includes =E2=80=9Cgetting off to a quick start and =
staying on that pace.=E2=80=9D And there was Trump, himself, calling into t=
he <strong>Hugh
Hewitt</strong> show this morning to discuss whether Republicans should pur=
sue a single massive budget reconciliation bill with all the G.O.P. menu it=
ems bundled together=E2=80=94=E2=80=9Cone big, beautiful bill=E2=80=9D=E2=
=80=94or deal with the border and taxes in separate bills. Trump said he=E2=
=80=99d be open to either, =E2=80=9Cas long as we get something passed as q=
uickly as possible.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=
=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Trump and his deputies a=
re communicating something critical in
the days before his second term begins. Even as he returns to office with f=
ull Republican control of government, unrivaled attentional powers, and Ova=
l Office experience under his belt, Trump simply doesn=E2=80=99t have the <=
em>time</em> to push all his campaign promises through Congress before his =
presidency starts to give off the stench of lame duck. Sure, he made histor=
y in November by winning the presidency again after four years in exile. Bu=
t he also made history in a way that doesn=E2=80=99t exactly work
in his favor: Trump is now the first president in the post-<strong>F.D.R.</=
strong> era to be limited by law to just a single term.=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bott=
om:0px;">Unlike in 2017, when a shell-shocked Washington establishment was =
contemplating the horror of an eight-year Trump run, D.C. pros this time ar=
ound are mostly just eyeing the next two years. Trump is a known commodity.=
 The midterm season arrives in 18 months or so, and
Democrats could easily flip the House. After that, media attention inevitab=
ly drifts to the next presidential election and the long primary process. S=
ure, by that time, the 81-year-old Trump will still have the nuclear codes =
and the power of the executive order. But as <strong>George W. Bush</strong=
>, <strong>Barack Obama</strong>, Trump 1.0, and <strong>Joe Biden</strong>=
 learned, presidents usually just walk through mud in their final two years=
 before leaving office.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;
margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">This=
 is why Republicans are so determined to jam their agenda through using the=
 budget reconciliation process, which requires only a simple majority vote =
for passage. But right now, Republicans are working with just a one-vote ma=
rgin in the House, meaning they need absolute party unity to pass a border =
bill or a tax bill or one big, beautiful bill. And Trump will never have mo=
re political capital than he does on January 19.
=E2=80=9CTime is not on their side,=E2=80=9D said <strong>Ron Bonjean</stro=
ng>, a longtime Republican strategist and veteran of many Capitol Hill batt=
les. =E2=80=9CThe first two years are going to matter greatly, here. People=
 talk about the first 100 days, but it=E2=80=99s probably going to take six=
 to seven months to get their significant legislation through, whatever it =
looks like. And that is paramount, because then the House campaign cycle st=
arts to kick in, with primaries and all the positioning that comes with it.=
=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D=
"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Another plugged-in Republican veteran of Capi=
tol Hill I spoke with Monday was not as charitable when I asked if Trump wi=
ll be able to muscle through whatever he wants. The tax bill will have to g=
et done somehow, this person told me, simply because the 2017 law is expiri=
ng this year. As for everything else? =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t think that t=
hey are going to get a lot done,=E2=80=9D this person said. =E2=80=9CI don=
=E2=80=99t know Susie Wiles that
well. She seems to have a good rep. But with the combination of Trump=E2=80=
=99s lack of discipline, and the House being a complete shitshow, they=E2=
=80=99ll be lucky to get anything big done. The Senate, I think, will be an=
 oasis of normalcy.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=
=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">California Senator <strong>Adam Schiff</st=
rong>=E2=80=94one of Trump=E2=80=99s most vocal Democratic critics, newly p=
romoted from the House=E2=80=94told me Monday that Republicans are setting =
up an aggressive voting
schedule for the new Congress, suggesting they can=E2=80=99t risk losing th=
e early momentum. =E2=80=9CThey seem to see a very narrow window in which t=
o act on a partisan level, with a very narrow majority,=E2=80=9D Schiff sai=
d. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s clear they want to jam things through on a partisa=
n basis. So it=E2=80=99s one big reconciliation bill, or two, so they can c=
ram in as much as they can. But in the House, it will be tough for them to =
get their own people on board.=E2=80=9D</p></div>
